{{Use South African English|date=February 2017}} {{Infobox officeholder | honorific-prefix = | name = Deidre Carter | native_name = | native_name_lang = | honorific-suffix = MP | image = | image_size = 100 | smallimage = <!--If this is specified, "image" should not be.--> | alt = 98k | caption = Ms. Carter in 2016 | office = Member of the [[National Assembly of South Africa]] | term_start = 6 May 2009 | constituency = | predecessor = | successor = | majority = | prior_term = | office1 = Deputy Secretary-General of the [[Congress of the People (South African political party)|Congress of the People]] | predecessor1 = ''Office created'' | term_start1 = November 2008 | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | citizenship = | nationality = South African | party = [[Congress of the People (South African political party)|Congress of the People]] | otherparty = | spouse = | partner = <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married--> | relations = | children = | residence = [[Pietermaritzburg]], [[KwaZulu-Natal]], [[South Africa]] | education = | alma_mater = | occupation = Politician | profession = | known_for = | committees = | portfolio = | awards = <!-- For civilian awards - appears as "Awards" if |mawards= is not set --> | website = }}
'''Deidre Carter''' is a South African politician who has served as a Member of the [[National Assembly of South Africa]] since May 2009 representing the [[Congress of the People (South African political party)|Congress of the People]]. Carter also serves as Deputy Secretary-General of the Congress of the People.<ref>http://www.parliament.gov.za/live/content.php?Item_ID=184&MemberID=38</ref>
==Early life and career== Carter was born in the Free State but moved to KwaZulu-Natal in 1990. She owned several businesses including restaurants and hotels.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.congressofthepeople.org.za/content/page/parliament|title=Parliament – Congress of the People|publisher=}}</ref>
==Political career== Carter was a founding member of the Congress of the People and attended the first National Convention. After the conference she was elected Deputy Secretary-General of the party.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/Archives/Witness/Who-is-PMBs-Deidre-Carter-20150430|title=Who is PMB’s Deidre Carter?|publisher=}}</ref> She was selected as a candidate for the party and elected at the 2009 election. Carter entered politics due to her concern about crime and corruption, deterioration in the rule of law and problems in the public healthcare and education systems.
