The '''OpenCoffee Club''' is an [[Open knowledge|open concept]] originated in 2007<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indexventures.com/team/index/profile_id/10 |title=Team |publisher=Index Ventures |date= |accessdate=2013-04-16}}</ref> in [[London]] by Saul Klein,<ref>{{cite web|author=Pascal-Emmanuel Gobry | url=http://www.businessinsider.com/saul-klein-profile-2011-1?op=1#ixzz2OyYqpdKF |title=Meet Saul Klein, The Entrepreneur Turned VC Who Just Sold His Company To Amazon For $312 Million |publisher=Business Insider |date=2011-01-20 |accessdate=2013-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2011/0822/entrepreneurs-reshma-sohoni-saul-klein-silicon-valley.html |title=Who Needs Silicon Valley? |publisher=Forbes.com |date=2011-08-22 |accessdate=2013-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://readwrite.com/2007/05/23/the_open_coffee_club_movement |title=The OpenCoffee Club Movement |publisher=Readwrite.com |date=2007-05-22 |accessdate=2014-01-22}}</ref> one of the founders of [[Skype]]. The goal was to encourage entrepreneurs, developers and investors to become acquainted with each other in informal gatherings so that the investment industry become more transparent and thus to encourage [[entrepreneurship]].<ref>[http://intruders.tv/en-tech/opencoffee-club-founder-saul-klein-from-index-ventures/ Interview with OpenCoffee Club founder Saul Klein] </ref>
Meetings are held worldwide every week at over 100 locations as the timing and content varies by city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.meetup.com/opencoffee/ |title=OpenCoffee communities |publisher=Meetup.com |date=2014-01-22 |accessdate=2014-01-22}}</ref>
